economic agents. It also provides methods of normative analysis which can be used to evaluate economic institutions, policies and projects.&amp;nbsp; Traditionally, both branches of economics have assumed that individuals have consistent and stable preferences. Descriptively, individuals are modelled as acting to satisfy their preferences; normatively, outcomes are judged good to the extent that preferences are satisfied. However, this assumption has been challenged by recent developments in behavioural economics&amp;nbsp;- a research programme which uses experimental methods and psychologically-based theories to investigate and explain behaviour.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This programme has discovered many robust regularities in behaviour which contravene standard assumptions about the consistency of individuals' preference, but which have credible psychological explanations. These developments are opening up a gap between descriptive and normative economics. This gap causes severe problems for standard economic methods of policy appraisal and, for some economists, raises doubts about the credibility of the behavioural approach. This project will explore and develop a range of possible solutions to the problem of reconciling normative and behavioural economics. A major objective is to draw economists' attention to this problem, and to foster debate about the relative merits of alternative solutions.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>361151</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>45DF8ABA-CDCD-4BC4-B845-90959A05836A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Market simulation and the provision of public goods: A non-paternalistic response to anomalies in environmental evaluation</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Environmental Economics and Management</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/18d7bb5c3d7f0aa2014d442bd7821752"><gtr:id>18d7b